
Legal Rights Navigator – Project Context

Legal Rights Navigator is an AI-powered legal assistant for Indian citizens. It helps users understand their legal rights, receive legal guidance, and generate structured legal documents such as complaints and notices. It is not a substitute for a lawyer and should always ground responses in retrieved legal sources.

Tech Stack

* Frontend: Next.js + React
* Backend: FastAPI
* AI Orchestration: LangGraph
* Database: PostgreSQL + PGVector
* Authentication: Google OAuth + JWT (HttpOnly Cookies)
* Embeddings: OpenAI text-embedding-3-small

Core Architecture

Every request follows this pipeline:

User Query
    ↓
Validity Gate
    ↓
Domain Classifier
    ↓
Clarification (if needed)
    ↓
Hybrid Retriever
    ↓
Legal Planner
    ↓
Advice / Document Generator
    ↓
Response

The retriever always performs domain metadata filtering before semantic search to avoid retrieving laws from unrelated domains.

Supported Domains

* Labour & Employment
* Consumer Protection
* Tenant & Property
* Cyber Crime
* Family & Women’s Rights

Each domain has its own prompts, templates, and legal knowledge base.

Conversation Memory

The system maintains:

* Sliding window of recent messages
* Structured extracted legal facts
* Rolling conversation summaries

This allows long-running legal conversations while keeping token usage bounded.

Current Development Goal

We are building the system incrementally. The current focus is implementing the Labour & Employment domain end-to-end, including ingestion, retrieval, LangGraph workflow, planning, response generation, and memory. Once complete, the same architecture will be replicated for the remaining domains.

Design Principles

* Never answer without retrieved legal context.
* Validate legal queries before processing.
* Use structured planner outputs instead of free-form reasoning.
* Generate complaints using templates, not unconstrained LLM output.
* Keep components modular and independently testable.

